<methodology slug="survey-design">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>user-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Six-step quantitative research process. Pre-register analysis, write neutral questions, structure flow, pilot with people, embed attention checks, report margins per segment.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>surveys</tag>
      <tag>quantitative-research</tag>
      <tag>survey-methodology</tag>
      <tag>product-research</tag>
      <tag>data-analysis</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Survey Design</title>
    <summary>A six-step process for designing surveys that produce valid quantitative data: define a single research objective, choose question types, write neutral non-hypothetical questions, structure the flow (screener → easy → core → demographics → open-end), pilot with 5-10 people, and pre-register the analysis plan before fielding. Surveys quantify hypotheses already shaped by 10+ qualitative interviews — they do not discover new problems.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Surveys without methodology training produce misleading data: leading questions bias responses, double-barreled items are uninterpretable, hypothetical questions ("would you pay $X?") predict nothing, and small-N segments reported as findings create false confidence. A bias-auditor agent pass over every instrument catches issues the drafting agent introduces. Pre-registering the analysis plan prevents fishing expeditions after data arrives.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Quantifying a hypothesis already shaped by 10+ qualitative interviews.</item>
        <item>Measuring satisfaction (CSAT, NPS, CES), feature priority (MaxDiff, Kano), or pricing (Van Westendorp, Gabor-Granger) over a defined population.</item>
        <item>Tracking a metric over time where comparability across waves matters more than depth.</item>
        <item>Screening a panel before booking interviews.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Discovery of unknown problems — interviews and analytics outperform surveys here.</item>
        <item>Segment N below ~30 where you intend to report on that segment (confidence intervals explode).</item>
        <item>Predicting future behaviour ("would you buy?") — ask about past behaviour only.</item>
        <item>Audiences who cannot self-report accurately (children, expert tasks, sensitive topics).</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Role of surveys">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run 10 or more customer interviews before designing a survey. Surveys quantify hypotheses shaped by qualitative research; they do not discover new problems.</statement>
        <rationale>Surveys without a qualitative foundation ask the wrong questions with high statistical precision and produce confidently wrong answers.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Pre-register the analysis plan and segment cuts before fielding — define which comparisons you will make and at what N threshold per segment. Surveys without pre-registration become fishing expeditions.</statement>
        <rationale>Post-hoc analysis finds patterns by chance; pre-registration forces honesty about what the survey is designed to answer.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Question writing rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Write neutral, non-hypothetical questions. Ask about past behaviour ("how often have you used...") not predictions ("would you use...").</statement>
        <rationale>Hypothetical questions systematically overpredict positive intent; past behaviour is a stronger predictor of future behaviour.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>One concept per question. Split double-barreled items into two separate questions.</statement>
        <rationale>Double-barreled items produce uninterpretable responses: agreeing could mean agreeing with either clause or both.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always include "Prefer not to say" or "Don't know" as response options. Forcing a choice corrupts data more than a missing response.</statement>
        <rationale>Forced-choice on unknowable items produces random noise distributed across the scale that looks like signal.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Randomize answer order on multiple-choice questions (eliminates primacy/recency bias) but keep ordinal scales fixed in direction.</statement>
        <rationale>Primacy and recency effects are large on long option lists; ordinal scales must be consistent to preserve comparability across respondents.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Leading question: "Do you like our product?"</description>
        <reason>Positive framing biases toward agreement; rewrite as "How would you rate your experience with [product]?" on a 1-5 scale.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Hypothetical: "How often will you use this feature?"</description>
        <reason>Predicts nothing; rewrite as "How often have you used similar features in other tools?"</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Survey structure and length">
      <p>Recommended flow: screener (1-2 qualifying questions) → easy openers (2-3 to build momentum) → core questions (5-10 main research) → demographics (3-5 for segmentation) → one open-end ("anything else?").</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Target 5-7 minutes total length for standard research surveys; pilot with 5-10 people to verify timing and cut 25% of questions you thought were essential.</statement>
        <rationale>Every minute above 7 minutes reduces completion rate by roughly 5-10%; abandonment at the end biases the completed sample toward highly engaged users.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Embed an attention check ("select 'agree' for this row") in any survey over 5 minutes; exclude respondents who fail.</statement>
        <rationale>Inattentive respondents produce random noise; they are detectable and removable without compromising sample integrity.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Report margin of error explicitly per segment, not just overall N. Any segment with N below 30 gets descriptives only — no recommendations.</statement>
        <rationale>Small segments reported as actionable findings are statistical noise dressed as insight.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Worked examples">
      <example type="good" title="Pricing survey">
        <note>Pricing survey for SaaS (n=150). Objective: determine acceptable price range for a new tier.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[Screener: "Do you currently use project management software?" (Yes → continue, No → end)
Q1: "How much do you pay monthly for PM tools?" [open numeric]
Q2-Q5: Van Westendorp (too cheap, cheap, expensive, too expensive) [open numeric x4]
Q6: "Which features would you pay extra for?" [multi-select]
Q7: "What would make a $49/mo plan worth it?" [open text]

Results (n=150):
- Optimal price: $29-39/month (Van Westendorp OPP)
- Must-have features: integrations, mobile app
- Insight: 85% expect annual discount option]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Feature prioritisation survey">
        <note>Feature prioritisation (n=200). Objective: decide next quarter's roadmap.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[Q1-Q3: MaxDiff (3 rounds, 4 features per round, balanced incomplete block design)
Q4: Satisfaction matrix (current features, 1-5 scale)
Q5: "What is the #1 thing you wish we would build?" [open text]

Results (n=200):
- Top priority: API access (38% best-of-set across MaxDiff rounds)
- Highest gap: Reporting (low satisfaction + high importance)
- Surprise: Mobile app less important than assumed]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic workflow and integration">
      <p>Drive survey design as a four-stage chain: (1) objective and decision framing, (2) instrument drafting, (3) bias review pass, (4) analysis-plan-before-distribution. Always run a separate critic agent over the question list — the drafting agent will not catch its own leading wording. Keep humans in the loop for translation, screener gates, and any incentive/compensation structure. After fielding, agents are good at descriptive stats and theme coding open-ends; they are bad at causal claims and significance testing without explicit stats tools.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: A market-researcher subagent as primary author for the instrument (best at JTBD-aligned phrasing). Use UX-researcher subagent as secondary for usability of the survey itself (length, mobile UX, drop-off prediction). A BA-modeling subagent for quantitative analysis pass (cross-tabs, segmentation, Van Westendorp curve fitting). A fresh-context critic instance (same model, no priors) for bias and leading-question review of the drafted instrument.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Survey design prompt pattern">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Role: survey methodologist.
Objective: <single decision the survey will inform>.
Audience: <segment + size>.
Constraints: <=7 min, ≤12 questions, mobile-first, neutral wording.
Forbidden: hypotheticals, double-barreled, leading, "would you", absolute time bins.
Deliver: screener (1-2 Q) → easy openers (2) → core (5-8) → demographics (3) → 1 open-end. JSON.]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Bias auditor prompt pattern">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Role: bias auditor. Input: survey JSON.
For each question, flag: leading, double-barreled, hypothetical, vague scale, missing "prefer not to say", reverse-coded inconsistency. Return list of {qid, issue, suggested_rewrite}.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLM drafts a Likert 5 scale by default for every attitude question.</description>
        <reason>Use 7-point for nuanced attitude measurement where you need to detect small shifts; binary for behavioral self-report where ambiguity is the failure mode.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent summarises open-end responses with top-line themes and drops disconfirming quotes.</description>
        <reason>Require quote-with-respondent-ID grounding for every theme claim; disconfirming quotes are the most valuable signal in qualitative open-ends.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent generates MaxDiff with unbalanced item-to-set assignment.</description>
        <reason>MaxDiff requires balanced incomplete block design; unbalanced assignment produces biased utilities. Use Conjointly or Sawtooth, not agent-generated task lists.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent reports "NPS went up 3 points" without acknowledging the confidence interval.</description>
        <reason>Gate any NPS reporting through a stats checker tool; LLM-only NPS commentary is almost always underpowered and overconfident.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <p>LLM-generated questions skew leading or double-barreled by default (the model wants to be helpful, helpfulness reads as bias). Free-text responses look themable to an agent even when they are not — small-N noise read as signal. Likert/NPS analysis with N less than 100 produces unstable scores; agents will report "5% NPS drop" that is inside the confidence interval. Translation/localization changes scale interpretation (East-Asian respondents underuse extreme scale ends — Western agents miss this). Distribution channel bias compounds silently: one Slack post produces a response set that looks "engaged users" not "users".</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Best practices and tools">
      <rule>
        <statement>Decide the analysis plan and segment cuts BEFORE fielding.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always include "Prefer not to say" / "Don't know" as response options.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Pilot with 5-10 humans, time them, then cut 25% of questions you thought were essential.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Randomize answer order on multi-choice but keep ordinal scales fixed.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>For MaxDiff, use a tool that runs proper experimental design (balanced incomplete block).</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Embed an attention check in any survey over 5 minutes; reject responders who fail.</statement>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Report margin of error explicitly per segment, not just overall N.</statement>
      </rule>
      <p>CLI tools: surveyjs-cli converts JSON spec to renderable survey JSON. pandas and pingouin provide cross-tabs, chi-square, ANOVA, effect sizes from CSV exports. bertopic and top2vec theme-cluster open-ended responses at scale. qsf-tools parses and diffs Qualtrics survey definitions for version control. R-cmdr (psych package) computes Cronbach alpha, factor analysis, and scale reliability.</p>
      <p>SaaS platforms: Qualtrics (enterprise, full panel, advanced logic) with REST API and Python SDK. Typeform (best UX, weak for matrix questions) with REST API and webhooks. SurveyMonkey (OK API, reasonable branching) with REST API. Tally (cheap free tier) with webhook only. Formbricks (open-source, self-host) with REST and JS SDK. LimeSurvey (heavy but full-featured, OSS) with RemoteControl 2 JSON-RPC API. Pollfish and Prolific (paid panels) with REST API for audience specification. Google Forms (internal use only) with Apps Script. MaxDiff via Sawtooth or Conjointly (required for proper balanced design). Otter.ai and Fireflies.ai (sales-call transcription source) with REST API. Gong and Chorus (sales-call goldmine for B2B) with REST API. Zendesk and Intercom (support-ticket pattern source) with REST API. Posthog (behavioral cohorts to validate) with REST API, SaaS or OSS.</p>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/survey-design-doc.md" purpose="Survey design document with objective, screener, core questions, analysis plan"/>
      <template path="templates/question-bank.md" purpose="Reusable questions for pricing (Van Westendorp), satisfaction (NPS), feature priority (MaxDiff)"/>
      <template path="templates/vw-pricing.py" purpose="Van Westendorp price-sensitivity analysis from CSV export"/>
    </templates>
